 The National Bureau of Statistics (NBS) yester day said in January 2021, inflation rate rose to 16.47 per cent. It was 15.75 per in December, which is an indication that the rate soared by 0.72 per cent in the period under review. NBS made this known in its data entitled: “Consumer Price Index January 2021(Base Period December 2009 -100).’’ According to the report, “The consumer price index, (CPI), which measures inflation, increased by 16.47 per cent (year-on-year) in January 2021. “This is 0.71 per cent points higher than the rate recorded in December 2020 (15.75 per cent). Increases were recorded in all COICOP divisions that yielded the Headline index.” NBS noted that the change in the average composite CPI for the 12-month period ending January 2021 over the average of the CPI for the previous 12-month period was 13.62 per cent, representing a 0.37 percentage point increase over 13.25 per cent it recorded last December. It said on month-on-month basis, the Headline index increased by 1.49 percent in January 2021. This, said the NBS, is 0.12 percentage points lower than the rate it recorded last December (1.61 percent). It further noted that on  month-on-month, the urban index rose by 1.52 per cent in January 2021, down by 0.13 percentage points when compared to the rate it recorded last December, while the rural index also rose by 1.46 per cent in January 2021, down by 0.12 compared to the rate that was recorded last December  (1.58 per cent). Besides, the report said the urban inflation increased by 17.03 per cent (year-on-year) in January 2021 from 16.33 per cent it recorded last December, while the rural inflation rate increased by 15.92 per cent in January 2021 from 15.20 per cent in December 2020. Meanwhile, NBS explained that  the corresponding 12-month year-on-year average percentage change for the urban index was 14.23 per cent in January 2021. This, it said, is higher than the 13.86 per cent reported last December, while the  corresponding rural inflation rate in January 2021 was 13.04 percent compared to 12.67 per cent recorded in December 2020. On All Item Index, the Bureau said the composite food index rose by 20.57percent in January 2021 compared to 19.56 per cent in December 2020. 